  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 4:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὗτος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": “He, as in R.V. All E.V[152] previously translated it “this,” referring it to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ λίθος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but in the next verse a person is directly spoken of, not under the metaphor of a stone, and the pronoun finds its subject better in the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐν τούτῳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", masculine of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 4:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See Winer-Schmiedel, p. 216.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ ἐξουθενηθεὶς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": in the LXX and in the Gospels the word used is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀπεδοκίμασαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". St. Peter, quoting apparently from memory, used a word expressing still greater contempt. It is used, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", very significantly by St. Luke in his Gospel, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 18:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word is found in none of the other Gospels, and is characteristic of St. Luke and of St. Paul (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 14:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 14:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 1:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 6:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). It occurs several times in the LXX; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Wis 3:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Wis 4:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Sir 19:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Ma 1:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Psalms of Solomon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 2:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In classical writers it is not found at all.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ γενόμ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εἰς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “which was made,” R.V. Blass compares the Hebrew phrase ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "הָיָהלְ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and finds parallels in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 13:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γίγνεσθαι εἰς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", while common in the LXX, is a correct expression in classical Greek, although the places in the N.T. in which the formula is found in O.T. quotations are undoubtedly Hebraisms (see below on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Winer-Schmiedel, p. 257, and with this may be connected the frequency of its occurrence in the Apocalypse (see Simcox on the phrase, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Language of the N. T.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 143).—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κεφαλὴν γωνίας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": not “the top-most pinnacle-stone,” but a corner-stone uniting two walls, on which they rested and were made firm, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the meaning of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀκρογωνιαῖος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 28:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 2:6-8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 2:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is used here by Symmachus instead of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κεφ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Hebrew ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "פִּנָּה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " elsewhere always refers not to the upper part of the building, but to the lower (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 28:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 51:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 38:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ βαλὼν λίθον γωνιαῖον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Delitzsch). Probably therefore the expression here refers to a foundation-stone at the base of the corner. On the occurrence of the phrase from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 118:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in St. Peter’s First Epistle, and in his speech here, see p. 119, and also Scharfe, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Die Petrinische Strömung",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 2 c., p. 126.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
